MEDIUM|internal/mcp/handlers.go:320|handleReconcile hardcodes reconcile.Options{Root: "."} for Epic 5.0 path validation, while every other operation in the same handler routes its base directory through e.root (gitrange.Resolve at 153/160/184, LoadReviewConfig at 198/607, Repo+Root at 205-206, verify.Verify at 556). The two values are equal only because cmd/atcr/serve.go:42 passes ".", so e.root == ".". It is correct by coincidence, not construction: if e.root ever diverges from CWD (a future serve --root flag, or an embedder constructing the engine with a non-"." root such as the test temp dir), file-existence validation resolves finding paths against the process CWD while the rest of the handler resolves against e.root — falsely flagging every path as "file not found".|Change handlers.go:320 from Root: "." to Root: e.root so path validation shares the same base directory as every other operation in the handler. Verify by constructing an engine with a non-"." root and asserting reconcile validation stats against e.root, not CWD.|correctness|15|internal/mcp/handlers.go:317-321|claude
MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/emit.go:85|JSONFinding.PathValid is a bool with json:"path_valid,omitempty": PathValid=true serializes "path_valid":true, but BOTH "validated, file missing" and "never validated" serialize as absent (false). The field's own 6-line CONTRACT comment (emit.go:79-84) warns consumers it MUST NOT be read in isolation. Shipping a wire field the authors document as untrustworthy is a footgun: a downstream consumer writing `if !path_valid` conflates a clean unvalidated finding with a confirmed-missing one. Both adversarial reviewers independently flagged this.|Drop path_valid from the findings.json schema entirely (only path_warning is load-bearing and unambiguous, and the report/checklist renderers already key solely off path_warning), OR change PathValid to *bool so nil (never validated) / true / false (validated-missing) are distinguishable. Verify findings.json byte-identity for the valid-path case if removed.|maintainability|30|internal/reconcile/emit.go:74-87|claude
LOW|internal/stream/validate.go:59|ValidatePath uses os.Stat, which follows symlinks, after only a lexical (no EvalSymlinks) containment check. If the reviewed repo contains a symlink (e.g. link -> /etc), a reviewer-controlled File="link/passwd" passes the lexical ".." guard (the cleaned path has no ".."), then os.Stat resolves through the symlink and reports existence of a file outside the repo — PathValid=true with no warning leaks one bit about the host filesystem into findings.json. The doc comment at line 51 claims lexical containment is "proportionate"; it is not airtight against symlinks. Requires an attacker controlling both a repo symlink and the finding path, hence low.|Use os.Lstat instead of os.Stat so a symlinked segment is not traversed, OR call filepath.EvalSymlinks on the joined path and re-check containment before stat. Add a test with a repo containing link -> /tmp and File="link/known" asserting the path is flagged invalid.|security|60|internal/stream/validate.go:46-70|claude
LOW|internal/stream/validate.go:59|A File equal to "." or to an existing directory (e.g. "internal") joins to a path that os.Stat resolves successfully, so ValidatePath stamps PathValid=true / PathWarning="". A finding whose "file" is the repo root or a directory is silently treated as a valid file location, contradicting Epic 5.0's purpose of flagging paths that do not point at a real reviewed file. Verified: root=".", File="." → rel="." → containment guard passes → stat succeeds → flagged valid.|After a successful os.Stat, reject directories: if info.IsDir() set PathValid=false and PathWarning=PathNotFoundWarning (or a distinct "not a file" warning). Add tests for File="." and File="internal" (an existing dir) asserting a warning is stamped.|correctness|15|internal/stream/validate.go:59-66|claude
LOW|internal/stream/validate.go:67|The default branch of the stat switch (indeterminate errors: permission, I/O) leaves PathValid/PathWarning untouched and swallows the error with no log or metric. The finding is left unflagged and, under omitempty, indistinguishable from a validated-and-present finding. An unreadable real file is reported with no caveat and the underlying stat error is undiagnosable.|Emit a debug-level log (with the joined path and error) in the default branch so the swallowed stat failure is diagnosable, or introduce a distinct "path unverified" warning state. Verify by stat'ing a path under a 0000-permission directory.|error-handling|30|internal/stream/validate.go:67-70|claude
LOW|internal/stream/validate.go:32|Existence is checked with os.Stat, which is case-insensitive on the default macOS (APFS) and Windows filesystems. A reviewer hallucinating a case-variant path (Parser.go for parser.go, internal/Stream/parser.go) resolves as present and is NOT flagged on the maintainer's own darwin platform — the platform most reviews run on, and case-typos are among the most common hallucination forms. The limitation is documented (validate.go:32-35) and deferred to TD, but there is no test pinning the gap.|Implement a case-exact existence check: os.ReadDir the parent directory and confirm the leaf basename matches an entry by exact string compare (optionally per path segment), rather than trusting os.Stat. Until then, add a test (skipped on case-sensitive FS) documenting the gap so the deferral lives in code, not only prose.|testing|60|internal/stream/validate.go:32-35|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/validate.go:15|validateFindingPaths calls ValidatePath once per merged finding with no memoization, so multiple findings on the same file (common — several issues in one file) each incur an independent os.Stat syscall on the identical joined path. Negligible at typical review sizes but gratuitous redundant I/O for a repo-wide review producing hundreds of findings concentrated on a few files.|Cache existence results by joined path inside validateFindingPaths (a map[string]bool) and stamp from the cache, or document that finding count N is bounded small. Verify with a benchmark over ~500 findings sharing ~10 files.|performance|30|internal/reconcile/validate.go:11-18|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/gate.go:225|validateFindingPaths runs its per-finding os.Stat loop between Reconcile (gate.go:220) and the ctx.Err() check (gate.go:227), so the new I/O stage sits in an un-cancellable window even though RunReconcile's header (lines 160-161) advertises ctx is checked between Discover, Reconcile, and Emit. On a large finding set with a slow/networked filesystem a client cancel or server shutdown cannot interrupt the stat loop before Emit.|Move the ctx.Err() check to before validateFindingPaths, or check ctx inside the validation loop for large N. Verify a cancel issued during validation aborts before Emit.|performance|15|internal/reconcile/gate.go:220-229|claude
LOW|internal/report/render.go:320|The display literal "⚠️ File not found: %s" is hardcoded identically in render.go:320 and emit.go:323, and its spelling ("File not found") differs from the stored stream.PathNotFoundWarning constant ("file not found") — three independently-spelled copies of one concept across three files. A change to the warning copy must be made in two render sites and will silently diverge from the stored contract value; nothing ties them together.|Render the warning off the actual stored f.PathWarning value, or hoist the display format into one shared helper referenced by both renderers, so the displayed and stored strings share a single source of truth. Verify both renderers and the constant stay in sync.|maintainability|15|internal/report/render.go:318-322|claude
LOW|cmd/atcr/serve.go:42|atcr serve passes a literal "." as the engine root and no production code resolves a repo root or chdirs (grep for os.Chdir returns nothing). For the long-running stdio MCP server, "." is whatever CWD the MCP client launched the process with — for many clients the editor/agent home dir or "/", not the repo under review. When CWD is not the repo root, Epic 5.0 path validation joins every relative finding path against the wrong base and os.Stat fails IsNotExist, stamping path_warning="file not found" on EVERY finding. This is the false-flag failure mode the epic's design question raised; the whole codebase assumes CWD==repo so it is a pre-existing architectural assumption, but path validation is uniquely CWD-sensitive (a raw stat, unlike git which works from any subdir).|Resolve the reviewed repo root explicitly at serve startup (git rev-parse --show-toplevel) and pass that absolute path as the engine root, then validate against it (see the handlers.go:320 e.root item). At minimum document that atcr serve MUST be launched with CWD==repo root and consider failing fast when no git root is found at CWD. Links to the handlers.go:320 finding.|correctness|60|cmd/atcr/serve.go:38-43|claude

